<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many solar panels can fit on my roof?", answer: "The number of panels depends on your usable roof area and panel orientation. A standard residential panel is approximately 1.7m x 1.0m (5.6ft x 3.3ft). Divide your roof length and width by the panel dimensions to find how many fit in rows and columns. Portrait orientation typically fits more panels on wider roofs, while landscape works better on narrower, longer roofs." },
  { question: "How much electricity will my solar panels produce?", answer: "Annual output depends on the number of panels, their wattage, your location's peak sun hours, and system efficiency. The formula is: kW capacity x peak sun hours x 365 days x 0.80 efficiency factor. For example, a 6 kW system in an area with 5 peak sun hours produces approximately 8,760 kWh per year, enough to offset most of a typical household's electricity usage." },
  { question: "What are peak sun hours and how do I find mine?", answer: "Peak sun hours represent the number of hours per day when solar irradiance averages 1,000 watts per square meter. This is not the same as hours of daylight. The US averages 3-7 peak sun hours depending on location. The Southwest averages 5-7 hours, the Midwest 4-5 hours, and the Northeast and Northwest 3-4 hours. You can find exact values from the NREL Solar Resource Data." },
  { question: "What is the typical wattage of a residential solar panel?", answer: "Modern residential solar panels typically range from 350 to 450 watts, with 400 watts being the current standard for new installations. Higher wattage panels (up to 500W) are available but are more common in commercial applications. Panel efficiency has increased from around 15% to over 22% in the last decade, meaning fewer panels are needed for the same output." },
  { question: "Does panel orientation (portrait vs landscape) matter?", answer: "Yes, panel orientation affects how many panels fit on your roof. Portrait orientation (tall side vertical) works better on wider roofs, while landscape orientation (tall side horizontal) can fit more panels on roofs with limited width but more length. The electrical output per panel is the same regardless of orientation. Orientation also affects mounting rail layout and wind load considerations." }
]) %>

